Fairness Measurements in Super Simple Terms

These are just ways to check if the AI is fair. Think of them like â€œreport cardsâ€ for fairness.

â¸»

1. Disparate Impact (The 80% Rule)
	â€¢	What it asks:
ğŸ‘‰ â€œDo different groups get about the same chance of a positive outcome?â€
	â€¢	Example:
If 60% of men get approved for a loan, then at least 48% (80% of 60) of women should also get approved.
	â€¢	If not: unfair â†’ AI is favoring one group too much.

â¸»

2. Demographic Parity
	â€¢	What it asks:
ğŸ‘‰ â€œDo groups get the positive outcome equally often?â€
	â€¢	Example:
If 50% of men are approved, then roughly 50% of women should also be approved.
	â€¢	If not: unfair â†’ AI is giving unequal chances just based on group.

â¸»

3. Equalized Odds
	â€¢	What it asks:
ğŸ‘‰ â€œIs the AI equally accurate for all groups?â€
	â€¢	Example:
If the AI predicts who has a disease:
	â€¢	For men: 90% of sick people are caught.
	â€¢	For women: only 70% of sick people are caught.
Thatâ€™s unfair â†’ the AI is less accurate for women.

â¸»

4. Counterfactual Fairness
	â€¢	What it asks:
ğŸ‘‰ â€œIf I were the same person but only changed my race/gender, would the AIâ€™s decision change?â€
	â€¢	Example:
Same loan applicant, same income, same job.
If AI approves him as â€œJohnâ€ but rejects her as â€œJaneâ€ â†’ unfair.

â¸»

